org.jsonurl

Class Parser

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jsonurl.BaseJsonUrlOptions
      • org.jsonurl.Parser
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    JsonUrlOptions
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ValueFactoryParser

    public class Parser
extends BaseJsonUrlOptions
    A JSON→URL text parser.

    An instance of this class may be used to parse JSON→URL text. Each instance maintains a set of limits that are applied any time the parse(CharSequence, int, int, ValueType, ValueFactory) (or any of the related convenience methods are called). No other state maintained globally, so a single instance of this class is thread-safe so long as you:

    • Set limits in a single-threaded context and don't change them in individual threads.
    • Provide proper locking around the setter/getter methods on this class.
    Since:
    2019-09-01
    Author:
    jsonurl.org, David MacCormack

        public void setMaxParseChars(int maxParseChars)
        Set the maximum number of parsed characters. This provides a limit on the maximum number of characters that will be parsed before throwing an exception. The default value is DEFAULT_MAX_PARSE_CHARS.

      • parse

        public <V,C extends V,ABT,A extends C,JBT,J extends C,B extends V,M extends V,N extends V,S extends V> V parse(CharSequence text,
                                                                                                               int off,
                                                                                                               int length,
                                                                                                               Set<ValueType> canReturn,
                                                                                                               ValueFactory<V,C,ABT,A,JBT,J,B,M,N,S> factory)
        Parse the given JSON→URL text and return a JSON value. The parse will start at the character offset given by off, and length total characters will be parsed.

        The provided factory will be used to instantiate values, so this method is target API agnostic. The canReturn value may be used to limit what types are allowed in the response. If an invalid value type is found then a ParseException will be thrown.

        Parameters:
        text - the text to be parsed
        off - offset of the first character to be parsed
        length - a length, not an offset
        canReturn - set of allowed return types
        factory - a valid ValueFactory
        Returns:
        a factory-typed value
